{"title_page": "Icing (game)", "text_new": "{{Infobox game\n| name = Icing\n| subtitle = Drinking Game\n| image =\n| caption =\n| players = 2+\n| setup_time = none\n| playing_time = ongoing\n| blank_label = Alcohol used\n| blank_data = [[Smirnoff ice]]\n| skills = Chugging\n| origin =  Boston, MA \n}}\n\n'''Icing''' is a [[drinking game]] and [[internet meme]] popular in 2010, in which one person conceals a bottle of [[Smirnoff Ice]] in a place that another individual will find it: upon doing so, they are immediately required to kneel and drink it. If handing the bottle to the person, they must willingly touch the bottle, otherwise the individual attempting to ice, must get on one knee and drink<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.fortune.com/2010/05/26/news/companies/bros_icing_bros.fortune/index.htm|title=Bros Icing Bros - May. 26, 2010|website=archive.fortune.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cracked.com/blog/icing-more-like-bullshit|title=Bros Icing Bros: Understanding This Ridiculous Phenomenon|date=June 11, 2010|website=Cracked.com}}</ref> Participants are encouraged to come up with elaborate ways to present the Smirnoff Ice to their targets by hiding bottles or cans in inconspicuous locations, or in situations where drinking it would be dangerous or embarrassing (e.g. before they attend a meeting).\n\n==Gameplay==\n\nA player hides a bottle for another person to come across. When the iced person sees the bottle, they must drop to one knee and chug the entire Ice. Other players who see the icer hide the Ice are exempt from drinking the ice. If the first person to touch the ice (the 'iced') fails to drink the whole bottle, the iced person cannot ice someone else.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.icingrules.com/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110053712/http://www.icingrules.com/# |archive-date=2012-11-10 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nAn Ice block occurs when the iced is already carrying a bottle of Ice on their person, or Kevin Renzo decides he doesn\u2019t want to drink one and claims he had one the whole time. If this happens, the icer (challenger) must drop and chug both Ices, the original presented Ice and the new blocking Ice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bros-icing-bros-the-new-binge-drinking-game-that-smirnoff-has-nothing-to-say-about/|title=Bros Icing Bros: The New Binge Drinking Game That Smirnoff Has Nothing to Say About|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\nIcing, which was described by ''The New York Times'' in June 2010 as \"the nation's biggest viral drinking game\",<ref name=NYT>Goodman, J. David. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/09/business/media/09adco.html Popular New Drinking Game Raises Question, Who\u2019s \u2018Icing\u2019 Whom?]\" ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 8, 2010. Retrieved on June 14, 2010</ref> grew in popularity shortly after the appearance of the website BrosIcingBros.com in May 2010.<ref>[[Matt T. Harvey|Harvey, Matt]]. \"[http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/iced_iced_baby_nA4JKpl5hU9Y8KshAwqbFK Iced, iced baby]\", ''[[The New York Post]]'', June 11, 2010. Retrieved on June 14, 2010</ref>\n\nThere has been some doubt<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Time>{{cite news|author= Quittner, Ella. |url= http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1997489,00.html|title= Bro Culture: Icing on the Social-Marketing Cake?|publisher= [[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= June 17, 2010|accessdate= January 17, 2012}}</ref> over whether this is an organic phenomenon<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Time/> or a marketing stunt by Smirnoff, which the company has denied.<ref name=NYT/> Advertising executive Dick Martin said \"Beyond the implicit slur on the beverage's taste, I doubt any alcoholic beverage company would want to be associated with a drinking game that stretches the boundaries of good taste and common sense like this one does\".<ref name=NYT/> The viral spread of the game has seen a boost in sales for the company.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Time/> Smirnoff insists that the game is \"consumer-generated\" and has reminded the public to drink responsibly,<ref name=NYT/> and [[Diageo]], the product's maker, stated \"that 'icing' does not comply with our marketing code, and was not created or promoted by Diageo, Smirnoff Ice, or anyone associated with Diageo.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Drink}}\n* [[List of drinking games]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Drinking games}}\n\n[[Category:Drinking games]]\n[[Category:Viral marketing]]\n[[Category:2010s fads and trends]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox game\n| name = Icing\n| subtitle = Drinking Game\n| image =\n| caption =\n| players = 2+\n| setup_time = none\n| playing_time = ongoing\n| blank_label = Alcohol used\n| blank_data = [[Smirnoff ice]]\n| skills = Chugging\n| origin =  Boston, MA \n}}\n\n'''Icing''' is a [[drinking game]] and [[internet meme]] popular in 2010, in which one person conceals a bottle of [[Smirnoff Ice]] in a place that another individual will find it: upon doing so, they are immediately required to kneel and drink it. If handing the bottle to the person, they must willingly touch the bottle, otherwise the individual attempting to ice, must get on one knee and drink<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.fortune.com/2010/05/26/news/companies/bros_icing_bros.fortune/index.htm|title=Bros Icing Bros - May. 26, 2010|website=archive.fortune.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cracked.com/blog/icing-more-like-bullshit|title=Bros Icing Bros: Understanding This Ridiculous Phenomenon|date=June 11, 2010|website=Cracked.com}}</ref> Participants are encouraged to come up with elaborate ways to present the Smirnoff Ice to their targets by hiding bottles or cans in inconspicuous locations, or in situations where drinking it would be dangerous or embarrassing (e.g. before they attend a meeting).\n\n==Gameplay==\n\nA player hides a bottle for another person to come across. When the iced person sees the bottle, they must drop to one knee and chug the entire Ice. Other players who see the icer hide the Ice are exempt from drinking the ice. If the first person to touch the ice (the 'iced') fails to drink the whole bottle, the iced person cannot ice someone else.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.icingrules.com/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110053712/http://www.icingrules.com/# |archive-date=2012-11-10 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nAn Ice block occurs when the iced is already carrying a bottle of Ice on their person, or is in reach of one without taking a step. If this happens, the icer (challenger) must drop and chug both Ices, the original presented Ice and the new blocking Ice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/bros-icing-bros-the-new-binge-drinking-game-that-smirnoff-has-nothing-to-say-about/|title=Bros Icing Bros: The New Binge Drinking Game That Smirnoff Has Nothing to Say About|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Popularity==\nIcing, which was described by ''The New York Times'' in June 2010 as \"the nation's biggest viral drinking game\",<ref name=NYT>Goodman, J. David. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/09/business/media/09adco.html Popular New Drinking Game Raises Question, Who\u2019s \u2018Icing\u2019 Whom?]\" ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 8, 2010. Retrieved on June 14, 2010</ref> grew in popularity shortly after the appearance of the website BrosIcingBros.com in May 2010.<ref>[[Matt T. Harvey|Harvey, Matt]]. \"[http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/iced_iced_baby_nA4JKpl5hU9Y8KshAwqbFK Iced, iced baby]\", ''[[The New York Post]]'', June 11, 2010. Retrieved on June 14, 2010</ref>\n\nThere has been some doubt<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Time>{{cite news|author= Quittner, Ella. |url= http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1997489,00.html|title= Bro Culture: Icing on the Social-Marketing Cake?|publisher= [[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= June 17, 2010|accessdate= January 17, 2012}}</ref> over whether this is an organic phenomenon<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Time/> or a marketing stunt by Smirnoff, which the company has denied.<ref name=NYT/> Advertising executive Dick Martin said \"Beyond the implicit slur on the beverage's taste, I doubt any alcoholic beverage company would want to be associated with a drinking game that stretches the boundaries of good taste and common sense like this one does\".<ref name=NYT/> The viral spread of the game has seen a boost in sales for the company.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=Time/> Smirnoff insists that the game is \"consumer-generated\" and has reminded the public to drink responsibly,<ref name=NYT/> and [[Diageo]], the product's maker, stated \"that 'icing' does not comply with our marketing code, and was not created or promoted by Diageo, Smirnoff Ice, or anyone associated with Diageo.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Drink}}\n* [[List of drinking games]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Drinking games}}\n\n[[Category:Drinking games]]\n[[Category:Viral marketing]]\n[[Category:2010s fads and trends]]\n", "name_user": "69.113.52.252", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eGameplay)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icing_(game)"}
{"title_page": "Willys\u2013Overland Building", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name           = Willys-Overland Building\n| nrhp_type      = \n| image          = Willys-Overland Building.jpg    \n| location       = 2300 Locust St., [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|38|38|8|N|90|12|44|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin       = United States St. Louis#USA\n| built          = 1917\n| architect      = [[Mills, Rhines, Bellman and Nordhoff]]\n| architecture   = Commercial [[Classical Revival]]\n| added          = 1999\n| governing_body = NSI Marketing\n| refnum         = 99001617\n}}\nThe '''Willys-Overland Building''' is a former automobile dealership and distribution building for the [[Willys|Willys-Overland Company]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] located at 2300 Locust Street.<ref name=\"nrhp\">{{Cite report |author=Karen Bode Baxter |date=August 9, 1999 |title=National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form for Willys-Overland Building |url=http://www.dnr.mo.gov/shpo/nps-nr/99001617.pdf |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> The building was the home of the company's main dealership and distributor in St. Louis from its completion in February 1917 until 1932, and upon its opening, it hosted the first indoor [[St. Louis Auto Show]].<ref name=\"nrhp\"/>\n\nThe building's exterior is a six-story brick facade with large windows on all sides and minimal ornamentation.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> Originally, the building had a showroom on its first floor, while upper floors included storage space and auto assembly rooms, connected by large freight elevators.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> The building also contained a body paint shop and a repair shop on its upper floors; to support the weight of the automobiles and shops, the floors are nearly one foot thick poured concrete.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/>\n\nAt the time of its construction, it was the largest automobile dealership and distribution center in St. Louis.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> As a result of its size, the organizers of the St. Louis Auto Show negotiated to rent the building for their annual show, which since 1907 had been held outdoors at [[Forest Park Highlands]].<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> By 1927, the company had expanded such that its used car dealership moved to an adjacent building and the company was operating a dozen dealerships in the area, but the building remained the corporations regional headquarters through 1932.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/>\n\nHowever, the [[Great Depression]] brought economic hardship to the company, and in 1932, the building was vacated; it remained vacant through 1935, when it was sold to the American Fixture and Manufacturing Company.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> In 1963, it again was sold, and since that time various small businesses occupied the first floor with little activity on its upper floors.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> In 1999, the building was nominated and accepted to the [[National Register of Historic Places]], and it underwent renovations by SJI Companies.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/><ref name=\"chaseco\">{{cite web |publisher=Chase and Company |title=2300 Locust |url=http://www.chaseco.net/images/2300_locust.pdf}}</ref> In 2005, the building received another renovation, costing $12 million, and it was renamed the NSI Building.<ref name=\"chaseco\"/><ref name=\"bsl\">{{cite web |author=Rob Powers |work=Built St. Louis |title=Locust Street |url=http://www.builtstlouis.net/central-corridor/downtown-west/locust-street01.html}}</ref><ref name=\"stlbj01222006\">{{cite news |author=Rick Desloge |date=January 23, 2006 |newspaper=St. Louis Business Journal |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/stories/2006/01/23/story1.html|title=National System sold to Chicago firm}}</ref> It currently is for sale for $17 million.<ref name=\"chaseco\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Willy's Overland Block]], Springfield, Massachusetts, also designed by [[Mills, Rhines, Bellman and Nordhoff]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Industrial buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Auto dealerships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Former auto dealerships]]\n[[Category:American Motors]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Downtown West, St. Louis]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name           = Willys-Overland Building\n| nrhp_type      = \n| image          = Willys-Overland Building.jpg    \n| location       = 2300 Locust St., [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\n| coordinates    = {{coord|38|38|8|N|90|12|44|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin       = United States St. Louis#USA\n| built          = 1917\n| architect      = [[Mills, Rhines, Bellman and Nordhoff]]\n| architecture   = Commercial [[Classical Revival]]\n| added          = 1999\n| governing_body = NSI Marketing\n| refnum         = 99001617\n}}\nThe '''Willys-Overland Building''' is a former automobile dealership and distribution building for the [[Willys|Willys-Overland Company]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]] located at 2300 Locust Street.<ref name=\"nrhp\">{{Cite report |author=Karen Bode Baxter |date=August 9, 1999 |title=National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form for Willys-Overland Building |url=http://www.dnr.mo.gov/shpo/nps-nr/99001617.pdf |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> The building was the home of the company's main dealership and distributor in St. Louis from its completion in February 1917 until 1932, and upon its opening, it hosted the first indoor [[St. Louis Auto Show]].<ref name=\"nrhp\"/>\n\nThe building's exterior is a six-story brick facade with large windows on all sides and minimal ornamentation.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> Originally, the building had a showroom on its first floor, while upper floors included storage space and auto assembly rooms, connected by large freight elevators.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> The building also contained a body paint shop and a repair shop on its upper floors; to support the weight of the automobiles and shops, the floors are nearly one foot thick poured concrete.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/>\n\nAt the time of its construction, it was the largest automobile dealership and distribution center in St. Louis.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> As a result of its size, the organizers of the St. Louis Auto Show negotiated to rent the building for their annual show, which since 1907 had been held outdoors at Forest Park Highlands.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> By 1927, the company had expanded such that its used car dealership moved to an adjacent building and the company was operating a dozen dealerships in the area, but the building remained the corporations regional headquarters through 1932.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/>\n\nHowever, the [[Great Depression]] brought economic hardship to the company, and in 1932, the building was vacated; it remained vacant through 1935, when it was sold to the American Fixture and Manufacturing Company.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> In 1963, it again was sold, and since that time various small businesses occupied the first floor with little activity on its upper floors.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/> In 1999, the building was nominated and accepted to the [[National Register of Historic Places]], and it underwent renovations by SJI Companies.<ref name=\"nrhp\"/><ref name=\"chaseco\">{{cite web |publisher=Chase and Company |title=2300 Locust |url=http://www.chaseco.net/images/2300_locust.pdf}}</ref> In 2005, the building received another renovation, costing $12 million, and it was renamed the NSI Building.<ref name=\"chaseco\"/><ref name=\"bsl\">{{cite web |author=Rob Powers |work=Built St. Louis |title=Locust Street |url=http://www.builtstlouis.net/central-corridor/downtown-west/locust-street01.html}}</ref><ref name=\"stlbj01222006\">{{cite news |author=Rick Desloge |date=January 23, 2006 |newspaper=St. Louis Business Journal |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/stories/2006/01/23/story1.html|title=National System sold to Chicago firm}}</ref> It currently is for sale for $17 million.<ref name=\"chaseco\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Willy's Overland Block]], Springfield, Massachusetts, also designed by [[Mills, Rhines, Bellman and Nordhoff]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Industrial buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Commercial buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Auto dealerships of the United States]]\n[[Category:Former auto dealerships]]\n[[Category:American Motors]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places]]\n[[Category:Transportation buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Downtown West, St. Louis]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in Missouri]]\n", "name_user": "DiamondRemley39", "label": "safe", "comment": "Linked new article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willys%E2%80%93Overland_Building"}
{"title_page": "Mini Ladd", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Northern Irish YouTube personality}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name                 = Craig \"Mini Ladd\" Thompson\n| logo                 = \n| logo_caption         = \n| image                =\n| caption              =Thompson in June 2019 \n| birth_name           =\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|df=y|1995|1|7\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCUfF2SXdGNXmi1XcZoqj8oQ Craig Thompson]\n}}\n| channel_display_name = \n| years_active         = 2011\u2013present (second channel created in 2015, third channel created in 2018)\n| genre                = [[Let's Play]], [[vlog]]s, [[reaction video]]s\n| subscribers          = {{plainlist|\n* 5.75&nbsp;million (Mini Ladd)\n* 1.14&nbsp;million (Craig Thompson)\n* 232,000 (Mini Ladd Vault)\n}}\n| subscriber_date      =\n| views                = {{plainlist|\n* 1.3&nbsp;billion (Mini Ladd)\n* 98 million (Craig Thompson)\n* 1.4&nbsp;million (Mini Ladd Vault)\n}}\n| view_date            =25 February 2020\n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n| catchphrase(s)       = \n| silver_button        = Yes\n| silver_year          = 2013 (Mini Ladd)\n2018 (Craig Thompson)\n\n2019 (Mini Ladd Vault)\n| gold_button          = Yes\n| gold_year            = 2014 (Mini Ladd)\n2019 (Craig Thompson)\n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = 25 February 2020\n}}\n'''Craig Thompson''' (born 7 January 1995), is an entertainer, comedian, vlogger, gamer and YouTuber, known by the online community as '''Mini Ladd'''. As of August 2019, he has accumulated over 10 million followers across all social platforms (YouTube, Twitter and Instagram), over 1.4&nbsp;billion views<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/miniladdd|title=miniladdd YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics |website=socialblade.com|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref>, and averages roughly 50,000 concurrent viewers during his live-streams. In September 2019, Thompson was named No. 3 out of the Top 100 Influencers in the UK by the ''Sunday Times''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-sunday-times-influencer-list-2019-meet-the-uks-top-100-hsmhv8dlp|title=The Sunday Times Influencer List 2019: meet the UK's top 100|last=Times|first=The Sunday|date=8 September 2019|access-date=18 September 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{Advert section|date=September 2019}}\nCraig launched his first YouTube channel, \"Mini Ladd\", in May 2011, posting gaming-related content that has since evolved into more of a comedic angle. Craig's content is witty, relatable and on-trend with the always-evolving online culture. In 2018, he launched his second channel, \"Craig Thompson\", which focuses on vlog and personal content, along with occasional videos on his [[Reddit]] subpage. In 2019, he launched his third YouTube channel, \"Mini Ladd Vault\" (which was first registered in 2015), where he uploads old videos from his Mini Ladd channel that had previously been demonetised.  \n\nCraig is committed to philanthropic work, having raised over $150,000 for the Thirst Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/4th-socialgood/craig-mini-ladd-thompson-and-the-thirst-project|title=Craig 'Mini Ladd' Thompson and Thirst Project \u2013 The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref>, a non-profit that builds water wells in the poorest countries around the world. In addition to raising money, he also spent 2 weeks in Swaziland in November 2018 building the water wells his community raised money for. Due to his ongoing efforts for the organisation, in 2019, the Thirst Project named Craig as one of their Board Members<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thirstproject.org/about/our-board/|title=Our Board|website=Thirst Project|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref> and awarded him with the \"Cameron Boyce Pioneering Spirit Award\" in October 2019. He has also donated large sums of money to organisations such as St. Jude, Macmillan Cancer Support and Northwest Counselling Ltd. Northwest Counseling's treasurer, Sean O'Kane, described Thompson's donation as a \"lifeline\" for the organisation.\n\nDue to his philanthropic efforts and growing celebrity, the [[City of Derry R.F.C.]] and his local rugby team renamed their stadium the \"[[Craig Thompson Stadium]]\" in his honour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derryjournal.com/sport/other-sport/youtube-sensation-takes-city-of-derry-global-1-8251383|title=YouTube sensation takes City of Derry Global!|website=derryjournal.com|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derrynow.com/sport/mini-ladd-becomes-mega-city-derry-rugby-club-sponsor/194412|title='Mini Ladd' becomes Mega City of Derry Rugby Club sponsor|last=Now|first=Derry|website=Derry Now|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref>\n \nIn 2017, Thompson moved to Los Angeles to continue expanding his career, before moving to [[Portland, Oregon]] in 2019 (he would return to Los Angeles a year later). In June of the same year, Craig and fellow YouTuber Anthony \"BigJigglyPanda\" Brown announced a tour called \"The Demonetized Tour\", which would take place across North America (mainly the United States and Canada) from September until December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/06/25/mini-ladd-bigjigglypanda-27-city-demonetized-tour/|title=Popular Gamers Mini Ladd And BigJigglyPanda To Embark On 27-City \u2018Demonetized\u2019 Tour|last=Weiss|first=Geoff|date=25 June 2019|website=Tubefilter|access-date=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miniladd.net/|title=Mini Ladd|website=miniladd.net|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref> In early 2020, Thompson confirmed that the tour could come to both Europe and Australia, although dates and cities are yet to be announced.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZG36pYrujIo</ref>\n\nIn September 2019 Craig was named by the Sunday Times as one of Britain's top 100 influencers, behind [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] and [[PewDiePie]].<ref name=\"thet_TheS\">{{Cite web |title=The Sunday Times Influencer List 2019: meet the UK's top 100 |work=The Times |date=8 September 2019 |access-date=16 January 2020 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-sunday-times-influencer-list-2019-meet-the-uks-top-100-hsmhv8dlp}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November 2019, Thompson won the eSports Content Creator of the Year award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esportznetwork.com/the-2019-esports-awards-winners/|title=The 2019 Esports Awards winners|date=17 November 2019|website=Esportz Network|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThompson was born in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] to an English father and a Northern Irish mother. He and his family moved to Northern Ireland, [[Eglinton, County Londonderry|Eglinton]],<!-- Please do not change Londonderry to Derry, as consistent with [[WP:LDERRY]] --> [[County Londonderry]], when he was ten years old. Before starting his online career, he was a student at [[Foyle College]], where he also played for the [[Rugby union|football]] team.\n\nIn February 2017, Thompson, alongside his friend and fellow YouTuber Jay, a.k.a. \"QwertyJaayy\", were hit by a [[Toyota Tacoma]] that had sped through a red light. Thompson suffered severe bruising and a cracked spleen, and was sent to the hospital for four days. Jay had suffered more severe injuries, and was sent to hospital in critical condition, eventually being placed in a coma for three weeks. For several weeks thereafter, Thompson required a walker (to which he dubbed \"[[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walker White]]\") to move around.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://youtube.com/watch?v=x-DIOJ0Eb5Y |title=This Is What Happened.|publisher=Mini Ladd|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Thompson began dating Twitch steamer Samantha Dey, aka SuniDey. In January 2020, Thompson announced on social media that they were no longer together.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://twitter.com/MiniLaddd/status/1213271829789306881|title=Please read:|publisher=MiniLaddd|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Thompson released a video titled \"Why I Left\", explaining details of why he left YouTube from late December, which included his return to his home in LA, him and SuniDey no longer in a relationship, and him wanting to improve things in his life, such as his mental health.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZG36pYrujIo]\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Release\n!No. of Tracks\n|-\n|''Disciple X Mini Ladd''\n|2018\n|15\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:People from County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Let's Players]]\n[[Category:Immigrants to Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:People educated at Foyle College]]\n[[Category:Northern Irish YouTubers]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dubai]]\n[[Category:Video bloggers]]\n\n\n{{YouTubers-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Northern Irish YouTube personality}}\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name                 = Craig \"Mini Ladd\" Thompson\n| logo                 = \n| logo_caption         = \n| image                =\n| caption              =Thompson in June 2019 \n| birth_name           =\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|df=y|1995|1|7}}\n| birth_place          = [[Dubai]], United Arab Emirates\n| death_date           = \n| death_place          = \n| nationality          = \n| residence            = Los Angeles, California\n| occupation           = YouTuber\n| website              =http://shopladd.com \n| pseudonym            = Mini Ladd\n| channels             = {{flatlist|\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/MiniLaddd Mini Ladd]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCUfF2SXdGNXmi1XcZoqj8oQ Craig Thompson]\n}}\n| channel_display_name = \n| years_active         = 2011\u2013present (second channel created in 2015, third channel created in 2018)\n| genre                = [[Let's Play]], [[vlog]]s, [[reaction video]]s\n| subscribers          = {{plainlist|\n* 5.75&nbsp;million (Mini Ladd)\n* 1.14&nbsp;million (Craig Thompson)\n* 232,000 (Mini Ladd Vault)\n}}\n| subscriber_date      =\n| views                = {{plainlist|\n* 1.3&nbsp;billion (Mini Ladd)\n* 98 million (Craig Thompson)\n* 1.4&nbsp;million (Mini Ladd Vault)\n}}\n| view_date            =25 February 2020\n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n| catchphrase(s)       = \n| silver_button        = Yes\n| silver_year          = 2013 (Mini Ladd)\n2018 (Craig Thompson)\n\n2019 (Mini Ladd Vault)\n| gold_button          = Yes\n| gold_year            = 2014 (Mini Ladd)\n2019 (Craig Thompson)\n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = 25 February 2020\n}}\n'''Craig Thompson''' (born 7 January 1995), is an entertainer, comedian, vlogger, gamer and YouTuber, known by the online community as '''Mini Ladd'''. As of August 2019, he has accumulated over 10 million followers across all social platforms (YouTube, Twitter and Instagram), over 1.4&nbsp;billion views<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/miniladdd|title=miniladdd YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics |website=socialblade.com|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref>, and averages roughly 50,000 concurrent viewers during his live-streams. In September 2019, Thompson was named No. 3 out of the Top 100 Influencers in the UK by the ''Sunday Times''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-sunday-times-influencer-list-2019-meet-the-uks-top-100-hsmhv8dlp|title=The Sunday Times Influencer List 2019: meet the UK's top 100|last=Times|first=The Sunday|date=8 September 2019|access-date=18 September 2019|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{Advert section|date=September 2019}}\nCraig launched his first YouTube channel, \"Mini Ladd\", in May 2011, posting gaming-related content that has since evolved into more of a comedic angle. Craig's content is witty, relatable and on-trend with the always-evolving online culture. In 2018, he launched his second channel, \"Craig Thompson\", which focuses on vlog and personal content, along with occasional videos on his [[Reddit]] subpage. In 2019, he launched his third YouTube channel, \"Mini Ladd Vault\" (which was first registered in 2015), where he uploads old videos from his Mini Ladd channel that had previously been demonetised.  \n\nCraig is committed to philanthropic work, having raised over $150,000 for the Thirst Project<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/4th-socialgood/craig-mini-ladd-thompson-and-the-thirst-project|title=Craig 'Mini Ladd' Thompson and Thirst Project \u2013 The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref>, a non-profit that builds water wells in the poorest countries around the world. In addition to raising money, he also spent 2 weeks in Swaziland in November 2018 building the water wells his community raised money for. Due to his ongoing efforts for the organisation, in 2019, the Thirst Project named Craig as one of their Board Members<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thirstproject.org/about/our-board/|title=Our Board|website=Thirst Project|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref> and awarded him with the \"Cameron Boyce Pioneering Spirit Award\" in October 2019. He has also donated large sums of money to organisations such as St. Jude, Macmillan Cancer Support and Northwest Counselling Ltd. Northwest Counseling's treasurer, Sean O'Kane, described Thompson's donation as a \"lifeline\" for the organisation.\n\nDue to his philanthropic efforts and growing celebrity, the [[City of Derry R.F.C.]] and his local rugby team renamed their stadium the \"[[Craig Thompson Stadium]]\" in his honour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derryjournal.com/sport/other-sport/youtube-sensation-takes-city-of-derry-global-1-8251383|title=YouTube sensation takes City of Derry Global!|website=derryjournal.com|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derrynow.com/sport/mini-ladd-becomes-mega-city-derry-rugby-club-sponsor/194412|title='Mini Ladd' becomes Mega City of Derry Rugby Club sponsor|last=Now|first=Derry|website=Derry Now|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref>\n \nIn 2017, Thompson moved to Los Angeles to continue expanding his career, before moving to [[Portland, Oregon]] in 2019 (he would return to Los Angeles a year later). In June of the same year, Craig and fellow YouTuber Anthony \"BigJigglyPanda\" Brown announced a tour called \"The Demonetized Tour\", which would take place across North America (mainly the United States and Canada) from September until December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tubefilter.com/2019/06/25/mini-ladd-bigjigglypanda-27-city-demonetized-tour/|title=Popular Gamers Mini Ladd And BigJigglyPanda To Embark On 27-City \u2018Demonetized\u2019 Tour|last=Weiss|first=Geoff|date=25 June 2019|website=Tubefilter|access-date=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://miniladd.net/|title=Mini Ladd|website=miniladd.net|access-date=12 August 2019}}</ref> In early 2020, Thompson confirmed that the tour could come to both Europe and Australia, although dates and cities are yet to be announced.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZG36pYrujIo</ref>\n\nIn September 2019 Craig was named by the Sunday Times as one of Britain's top 100 influencers, behind [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] and [[PewDiePie]].<ref name=\"thet_TheS\">{{Cite web |title=The Sunday Times Influencer List 2019: meet the UK's top 100 |work=The Times |date=8 September 2019 |access-date=16 January 2020 |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/the-sunday-times-influencer-list-2019-meet-the-uks-top-100-hsmhv8dlp}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 November 2019, Thompson won the eSports Content Creator of the Year award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.esportznetwork.com/the-2019-esports-awards-winners/|title=The 2019 Esports Awards winners|date=17 November 2019|website=Esportz Network|access-date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nThompson was born in [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]] to an English father and a Northern Irish mother. He and his family moved to Northern Ireland, [[Eglinton, County Londonderry|Eglinton]],<!-- Please do not change Londonderry to Derry, as consistent with [[WP:LDERRY]] --> [[County Londonderry]], when he was ten years old. Before starting his online career, he was a student at [[Foyle College]], where he also played for the [[Rugby union|football]] team.\n\nIn February 2017, Thompson, alongside his friend and fellow YouTuber Jay, a.k.a. \"QwertyJaayy\", were hit by a [[Toyota Tacoma]] that had sped through a red light. Thompson suffered severe bruising and a cracked spleen, and was sent to the hospital for four days. Jay had suffered more severe injuries, and was sent to hospital in critical condition, eventually being placed in a coma for three weeks. For several weeks thereafter, Thompson required a walker (to which he dubbed \"[[Walter White (Breaking Bad)|Walker White]]\") to move around.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://youtube.com/watch?v=x-DIOJ0Eb5Y |title=This Is What Happened.|publisher=Mini Ladd|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Thompson began dating Twitch steamer Samantha Dey, aka SuniDey. In January 2020, Thompson announced on social media that they were no longer together.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://twitter.com/MiniLaddd/status/1213271829789306881|title=Please read:|publisher=MiniLaddd|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Thompson released a video titled \"Why I Left\", explaining details of why he left YouTube from late December, which included his return to his home in LA, him and SuniDey no longer in a relationship, and him wanting to improve things in his life, such as his mental health.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZG36pYrujIo]\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Title\n!Release\n!No. of Tracks\n|-\n|''Disciple X Mini Ladd''\n|2018\n|15\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:People from County Londonderry]]\n[[Category:Let's Players]]\n[[Category:Immigrants to Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:People educated at Foyle College]]\n[[Category:Northern Irish YouTubers]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dubai]]\n[[Category:Video bloggers]]\n\n\n{{YouTubers-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:f0d:db00:ac16:d287:4ac2:dfef", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mini_Ladd"}
{"title_page": "Calcare di Sogno", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Calcare di Sogno\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = [[Toarcian]]<br>~{{fossil range|183|181}}\n| period         = Toarcian\n| prilithology   = [[Marl]], marly [[limestone]] & abundance of [[clay]]<br>Secondary: Alternation of marly limestones and [[marl]]s, presence of graded ''[[Chalcudites]]''\n| otherlithology = [[Limestone]]s with nodules of [[flint]] & subordinate marls\n| namedfor       = [[Sogno]]\n| namedby        = Gaetani & Poliani\n| region         = [[Lecco Province]]\n| country        = {{ITA}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|45.8|N|9.3|E|display=inline,title}}\n| unitof         =\n| subunits       = \n| underlies      = [[Formazione delle Radiolariti]]\n| overlies       = [[Calcare di Domaro]], [[Calcare di Morbio]], Unnamed limestones{{refn|group=note|Bioturbed hazel-gray limestones in planar layers of about 20 cm, with concentration of gray flint and gray & reddish marls, along with calcareous marl.<ref name=\"Sogno\"/>}}\n| thickness      = Typically {{convert|120|-|140|m|ft|abbr=on}}<br>East and west {{convert|70|-|100|m|abbr=on}}\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Calcare di Sogno''' (\"Sogno Limestone\"; also known as the '''Sogno Formation''') is a [[geological formation]] in [[Italy]], dated to roughly between 183-181 [[mya (unit)|million years ago]] and covering the [[Toarcian]] [[faunal stage|stages]] of the [[Jurassic]] Period in the [[Mesozoic Era]].<ref name=\"Sogno\">CARTA GEOLOGICA D\u2019ITALIA 1:50.000 - CATALOGO DELLE FORMAZIONE. Formazione di Sogno.SERVIZIO GEOLOGICO - CONSIGLIO NAZIONALE DELLE RICERCHE - COMMISSIONE ITALIANA DI STRATIGRAFIA: http://www.isprambiente.gov.it/files/pubblicazioni/periodicitecnici/quaderni-sgi/quad7/form5.pdf </ref> Thallatosuchian remains are know from the formation. The Formation is Characterised by a disposition of regional deposition equivalent to the German [[Posidonia Shale]], with a benthonic setting and deposition trends, mostly populated by marine fauna.<ref name=\"Gaetani\">GAETANI M. & POLIANI G. (1978) - Il Toarciano ed il Giurassico medio in Albenza (Bergamo). Riv. It. Pal. Strat., 84 (2): 349-382, 5 figg., 2 tavv., Milano.</ref>The environment of the formation was related to a marginal marine deposit, with probably epicontinetal deposition from near land environments, being connected to the central European seas of the Toarcian.<ref> GAETANI M. & ERBA E. (1990) - Il Bacino Lombardo: un sistema paleo alto/fossa in un margine continentale passivo durante il Giurassico. In: JADOUL F. & MASSIOTTA P. (Eds.): \u00abLa geologia italiana degli anni \u201990 - Guida alle escursioni pre-congresso\u00bb. 75\u00b0 Congr. Naz. Soc. Geol. It.: Escursione A3, pp. 23, 14 figg., 1 tav., Milano</ref><ref>DEL SERE M. (1966) - \u00abLagenidea\u00bb del Lias dell\u2019Albenza (Bergamo). Riv. It. Pal. Strat., 72 (1): 147-188, 2 figg.,4 tavv., Milano.</ref><ref> BERSEZIO R., JADOUL F. & CHINAGLIA N. (1997) - Geological map of the Norian-Jurassic succession of Southern\nAlps north of Bergamo: explanatory notes. Boll. Soc. Geol. It., 116 (2): 363-378, 1 carta geol., Roma</ref>\n\n== Fossil content ==\n=== Molluscs ===\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images\n|-\n| ''[[Hildaites]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/> \n| ''Hildaites sp.''\n| \n| \n| A  [[Hildoceratidae]] [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Hildaites fasciculatus.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Cornaptychus]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Cornaptychus lythensis''\n| \n| \n| An  indeterminate [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Cornaptychus lythensis.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Dactylioceras]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Dactylioceras polymorphus''\n| \n|\n| An  [[Dactylioceratinae]] [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Dactylioceras group.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Mesodactylites]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| \n*''Mesodactylites sapphicus''\n*''Mesodactylites sp.''\n|\n|\n| An  [[Nodicoeloceratinae]] [[ammonite]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Harpoceras]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Harpoceras sp.''\n| \n| \n| A [[Harpoceratinae]] [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Harpoceras NT.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Collina (ammonite)|Collina]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Collina gemma''\n| \n| \n| An  [[Dactylioceratidae]] [[ammonite]]\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Arthropods ===\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n''[[Proeryon]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Crustacea\">Garassino, A., & Gironi, B. (2005). Proeryon hartmanni (v. Meyer, 1835)(Crustacea, Decapoda, Eryonoidea) and Archaeopalinurus cfr. A. levis Pinna, 1974 (Crustacea, Decapoda, Palinuroidea) from the Lower Jurassic (Toarcian) of Cesana Brianza-Suello (Lecco, N Italy). Atti della Societ\u00e0 italiana di Scienze naturali e del Museo civico di Storia naturale in Milano, 146(1), 53-68.</ref>\n|\n''Proeryon hartmanni''\n|\n|\n|\nA Erymidae [[Decapoda]]n Crustacean common on the mediterranean rocks. Frequent presence of Burrows ''[[Thalassinoides]]'' with fossilised specimens nearby. A complete Seafloor section was fossilized.\n|\n[[File:Proeryon.JPG|200px]]\n|-\n|\n''[[Gabaleryon]]''<ref>Audo, D., Williams, M., Charbonnier, S., & Schweigert, G. (2017). Gabaleryon, a new genus of widespread early Toarcian polychelidan lobsters. Journal of Systematic Palaeontology, 15(3), 205-222.</ref>\n|\n''Gabaleryon garassinoi''\n|\n|\n|\nA [[Coleiidae]] [[Decapoda]]n. Was confussed with Proeryon hartmanni specimens.\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Archaeopalinurus]]''<ref name=\"Crustacea\"/>\n|\n''Archaeopalinurus cfr. A. levis''\n|\n|\n|\nA Palinuroidean [[Decapoda]]n.\n|\n[[File:Archaeopalinurus laevis Cene.JPG|200px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Vertebrates ==\n=== Fish ===\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n''[[Pholidophorus]]'' <ref name=\"Tintori\">A. Tintori. 1977. Toarcian fishes from the Lombardian basin. Bolletino della Societ\u00e0 Paleontologica Italiana 16:143-152 </ref><ref name=\"Pelago\">M. Delfino and C. Dal Sasso. 2006. Marine reptiles (Thalattosuchia) from the Early Jurassic of Lombardy (northern Italy). Geobios 39:346-354 </ref>\n|\n*''Pholidophorus'' sp.\n|\nMonte Cornizzolo\n|\nSeveral Especimens\n|\nType member of the family [[Pholidophoridae]] inside [[Pachycormiformes]]. A small sized fish, mostly related to marine deposits, asociated with various predatory behaviours, including coeloids and Crocodrylomorphs.\n|\n[[File:Pholidophorus NT.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|\n''[[Leptolepis]]''<ref name=\"Tintori\"/><ref name=\"Pelago\"/>\n|\t\n*''Leptolepis coryphaenoides''\n*''Leptolepis sp.''\n|\nMonte Cornizzolo\n|\nSeveral Especimens\n|\nType member of the family [[Leptolepidae]] inside [[Leptolepiformes]]\n|\n[[File:Leptolepis NT.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|\n''[[Pachycormus (fish)|Pachycormus]]''<ref name=\"Tintori\"/><ref name=\"Pelago\"/>\n|\t\n*''Pachycormus sp.'' \n|\nMonte Cornizzolo\n|\nSeveral Especimens\n|\nThe main member of the family [[Pachycormidae]] inside [[Pachycormiformes]]. Large sized fish, able to reach near 1.4 m long.\n|\n[[File:Pachycormus.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Crocodyliformes ===\n{|class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Location\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\ncf.''[[Pelagosaurus]]''<ref name=\"Pelago\"/>\n|\nIndeterminate\n|\nMonte Cornizzolo\n|\nVarious specimens MSNM V4012, MSNM V4013.\n|\n|\n[[File:Pelagosaurus BW.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of dinosaur-bearing rock formations]]\n* [[Toarcian turnover]]\n* [[:Category:Toarcian Stage|Toarcian formations]]\n** [[Marne di Monte Serrone]], Italy\n** [[Budo\u0161 Limestone]], Montenegro\n** [[Posidonia Shale]], [[Lagerst\u00e4tte]] in Germany\n** [[Ciechocinek Formation]], Czechia and Poland\n** [[Lava Formation]], Lithuania\n** [[Toundoute Continental Series]], North Africa\n** [[Whitby Mudstone]], England\n** [[Poker Chip Shale]], Alberta\n** [[Whiteaves Formation]], British Columbia\n** [[Navajo Sandstone]], Utah\n** [[Los Molles Formation]], Argentina\n** [[Mawson Formation]], Antarctica\n** [[Kandreho Formation]], Madagascar\n** [[Kota Formation]], India\n** [[Cattamarra Coal Measures]], Australia\n\n== Notes and references ==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==== Bibliography ====\n* {{cite LSA |last=[[David B. Weishampel|Weishampel]] |first=David B. |last2=[[Peter Dodson|Dodson]] |first2=Peter |last3=[[Halszka Osm\u00f3lska|Osm\u00f3lska]] (eds.) |first3=Halszka |year=2004 |title=The Dinosauria, 2nd edition |url=https://books.google.com.co/books/about/The_Dinosauria.html?id=vtZFDb_iw40C&redir_esc=y |publisher=Berkeley: University of California Press |pages=1\u2013880 |accessdate=2019-02-21}} {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calcari Grigi Di Noriglio Formation}}\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Italy]]\n[[Category:Jurassic System of Europe]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Italy]]\n[[Category:Toarcian Stage]]\n[[Category:Limestone formations]]\n[[Category:Marl formations]]\n[[Category:Shallow marine deposits]]\n[[Category:Fossiliferous stratigraphic units of Europe]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Italy]]\n[[Category:Province of Lecco|Formations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Calcare di Sogno\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = [[Toarcian]]<br>~{{fossil range|183|181}}\n| period         = Toarcian\n| prilithology   = [[Marl]], marly [[limestone]] & abundance of [[clay]]<br>Secondary: Alternation of marly limestones and [[marl]]s, presence of graded ''[[Chalcudites]]''\n| otherlithology = [[Limestone]]s with nodules of [[flint]] & subordinate marls\n| namedfor       = [[Sogno]]\n| namedby        = Gaetani & Poliani\n| region         = [[Lecco Province]]\n| country        = {{ITA}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|45.8|N|9.3|E|display=inline,title}}\n| unitof         =\n| subunits       = \n| underlies      = [[Formazione delle Radiolariti]]\n| overlies       = [[Calcare di Domaro]], [[Calcare di Morbio]], Unnamed limestones{{refn|group=note|Bioturbed hazel-gray limestones in planar layers of about 20 cm, with concentration of gray flint and gray & reddish marls, along with calcareous marl.<ref name=\"Sogno\"/>}}\n| thickness      = Typically {{convert|120|-|140|m|ft|abbr=on}}<br>East and west {{convert|70|-|100|m|abbr=on}}\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Calcare di Sogno''' (\"Sogno Limestone\"; also known as the '''Sogno Formation''') is a [[geological formation]] in [[Italy]], dated to roughly between 183-181 [[mya (unit)|million years ago]] and covering the [[Toarcian]] [[faunal stage|stages]] of the [[Jurassic]] Period in the [[Mesozoic Era]].<ref name=\"Sogno\">CARTA GEOLOGICA D\u2019ITALIA 1:50.000 - CATALOGO DELLE FORMAZIONE. Formazione di Sogno.SERVIZIO GEOLOGICO - CONSIGLIO NAZIONALE DELLE RICERCHE - COMMISSIONE ITALIANA DI STRATIGRAFIA: http://www.isprambiente.gov.it/files/pubblicazioni/periodicitecnici/quaderni-sgi/quad7/form5.pdf </ref> Thallatosuchian remains are know from the formation. The Formation is Characterised by a disposition of regional deposition equivalent to the German [[Posidonia Shale]], with a benthonic setting and deposition trends, mostly populated by marine fauna.<ref name=\"Gaetani\">GAETANI M. & POLIANI G. (1978) - Il Toarciano ed il Giurassico medio in Albenza (Bergamo). Riv. It. Pal. Strat., 84 (2): 349-382, 5 figg., 2 tavv., Milano.</ref>The environment of the formation was related to a marginal marine deposit, with probably epicontinetal deposition from near land environments, being connected to the central European seas of the Toarcian.<ref> GAETANI M. & ERBA E. (1990) - Il Bacino Lombardo: un sistema paleo alto/fossa in un margine continentale passivo durante il Giurassico. In: JADOUL F. & MASSIOTTA P. (Eds.): \u00abLa geologia italiana degli anni \u201990 - Guida alle escursioni pre-congresso\u00bb. 75\u00b0 Congr. Naz. Soc. Geol. It.: Escursione A3, pp. 23, 14 figg., 1 tav., Milano</ref><ref>DEL SERE M. (1966) - \u00abLagenidea\u00bb del Lias dell\u2019Albenza (Bergamo). Riv. It. Pal. Strat., 72 (1): 147-188, 2 figg.,4 tavv., Milano.</ref><ref> BERSEZIO R., JADOUL F. & CHINAGLIA N. (1997) - Geological map of the Norian-Jurassic succession of Southern\nAlps north of Bergamo: explanatory notes. Boll. Soc. Geol. It., 116 (2): 363-378, 1 carta geol., Roma</ref>\n\n== Fossil content ==\n=== Molluscs ===\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images\n|-\n| ''[[Hildaites]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/> \n| ''Hildaites sp.''\n| \n| \n| A  [[Hildoceratidae]] [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Hildaites fasciculatus.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Cornaptychus]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Cornaptychus lythensis''\n| \n| \n| An  indeterminate [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Cornaptychus lythensis.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Dactylioceras]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Dactylioceras polymorphus''\n| \n|\n| An  [[Dactylioceratinae]] [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Dactylioceras group.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Mesodactylites]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| \n*''Mesodactylites sapphicus''\n*''Mesodactylites sp.''\n|\n|\n| An  [[Nodicoeloceratinae]] [[ammonite]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Harpoceras]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Harpoceras sp.''\n| \n| \n| A [[Harpoceratinae]] [[ammonite]]\n| [[File:Harpoceras NT.jpg|200px]]\n|-\n| ''[[Collina (ammonite)|Collina]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Gaetani\"/>\n| ''Collina gemma''\n| \n| \n| An  [[Dactylioceratidae]] [[ammonite]]\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Arthropods ===\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n''[[Proeryon]]''<ref name=\"Sogno\"/><ref name=\"Crustacea\">Garassino, A., & Gironi, B. (2005). Proeryon hartmanni (v. Meyer, 1835)(Crustacea, Decapoda, Eryonoidea) and Archaeopalinurus cfr. A. levis Pinna, 1974 (Crustacea, Decapoda, Palinuroidea) from the Lower Jurassic (Toarcian) of Cesana Brianza-Suello (Lecco, N Italy). Atti della Societ\u00e0 italiana di Scienze naturali e del Museo civico di Storia naturale in Milano, 146(1), 53-68.</ref>\n|\n''Proeryon hartmanni''\n|\n|\n|\nA Erymidae [[Decapoda]]n Crustacean common on the mediterranean rocks. Frequent presence of Burrows ''[[Thalassinoides]]'' with fossilised specimens nearby. A complete Seafloor section was fossilized.\n|\n[[File:Proeryon.JPG|200px]]\n|-\n|\n''[[Gabaleryon]]''<ref>Audo, D., Williams, M., Charbonnier, S., & Schweigert, G. (2017). Gabaleryon, a new genus of widespread early Toarcian polychelidan lobsters. Journal of Systematic Palaeontology, 15(3), 205-222.</ref>\n|\n''Gabaleryon garassinoi''\n|\n|\n|\nA [[Coleiidae]] [[Decapoda]]n. Was confussed with Proeryon hartmanni specimens.\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Archaeopalinurus]]''<ref name=\"Crustacea\"/>\n|\n''Archaeopalinurus cfr. A. levis''\n|\n|\n|\nA Palinuroidean [[Decapoda]]n.\n|\n[[File:Archaeopalinurus laevis Cene.JPG|200px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Vertebrates ==\n=== Fish ===\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Stratigraphic position\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n|\n''[[Pholidophorus]]'' <ref name=\"Tintori\">A. Tintori. 1977. Toarcian fishes from the Lombardian basin. Bolletino della Societ\u00e0 Paleontologica Italiana 16:143-152 </ref><ref name=\"Pelago\">M. Delfino and C. Dal Sasso. 2006. Marine reptiles (Thalattosuchia) from the Early Jurassic of Lombardy (northern Italy). Geobios 39:346-354 </ref>\n|\n''Pholidophorus'' sp.\n|\nMonte Cornizzolo\n|\nSeveral Especimens\n|\nType member of the family [[Pholidophoridae]] ins